Switching from a WebView to the Native Mapbox SDK (v11+) is a big step up in performance. Since you are using a 2026 version of Android Studio and Jetpack Compose, you should use the official Mapbox Compose Extension.

Here is the exact way to set it up.

1. Configure Your Credentials (The "SK" vs "PK" Fix)
To download the SDK, you need a Secret Key (sk), but to run the map, you need a Public Key (pk).

Secret Key: Go to your Mapbox Dashboard, create a token with DOWNLOADS:READ scope.

gradle.properties: Open this file in your root folder and add:

Properties
MAPBOX_DOWNLOADS_TOKEN=sk.your_secret_key_here
Public Key: Open app/src/main/res/values/strings.xml and add:

XML
<string name="mapbox_access_token">pk.your_public_key_here</string>
2. Add Repositories and Dependencies
Modern Android Studio (Panda 2) uses settings.gradle.kts for repositories.

In settings.gradle.kts:

Kotlin
dependencyResolutionManagement {
    repositories {
        google()
        mavenCentral()
        // Add the Mapbox Maven repository
        maven {
            url = uri("https://api.mapbox.com/downloads/v2/releases/maven")
            credentials {
                username = "mapbox"
                password = providers.gradleProperty("MAPBOX_DOWNLOADS_TOKEN").get()
            }
        }
    }
}
In app/build.gradle.kts:

Kotlin
dependencies {
    // Standard Maps SDK + Compose Extension
    implementation("com.mapbox.maps:android:11.8.0")
    implementation("com.mapbox.extension:maps-compose:11.8.0")
}
3. The Native Compose Code
Replace your entire WebView logic with this clean, native implementation.

Kotlin
import com.mapbox.geojson.Point
import com.mapbox.maps.extension.compose.MapboxMap
import com.mapbox.maps.extension.compose.animation.viewport.rememberMapViewportState
import com.mapbox.maps.extension.compose.annotation.generated.PointAnnotation

@Composable
fun MapScreen() {
    val destination = Point.fromLngLat(106.70090, 10.77689)
    
    // Manage the camera state (Zoom, Center)
    val mapViewportState = rememberMapViewportState {
        setCameraOptions {
            center(destination)
            zoom(15.0)
            pitch(45.0) // 3D angle
        }
    }

    Column(modifier = Modifier.fillMaxSize()) {
        // Native Mapbox Composable
        MapboxMap(
            modifier = Modifier.fillMaxSize(),
            mapViewportState = mapViewportState,
        ) {
            // Native Marker (Annotation)
            PointAnnotation(
                point = destination,
                iconImage = "marker-15", // Uses default Mapbox icon
                onClick = {
                    // Handle click on the Nova building
                    true
                }
            )
        }
    }
}
4. Why this is better than your WebView code:
Gestures: Smooth 3D rotation and tilt with two fingers.

Battery: Native rendering (OpenGL/Vulkan) is much lighter on the battery than a Chrome-based WebView.

Caching: The SDK handles offline tile caching automatically.

Permissions: Mapbox v11 has a LocationComponent that handles the "Blue Dot" for user location with zero JavaScript needed.

Common Error: "403 Forbidden"
If your Gradle Sync fails with a 403 error, it means:

Your Secret Token (sk) doesn't have the DOWNLOADS:READ checkbox checked.

You typed the password/username wrong in settings.gradle.kts. (Username must always be exactly "mapbox").

